7. GOVERNANCE FRAMEWORK

7.1 NASAg: Neural Architecture Safety & Governance

Structure:

· 7 Regional Centers (one per continent)
· 21 Voting Members (3 per region, rotating)
· Technical Advisory Board (50 experts, rotating)
· Public Oversight Committee (civil society representatives)

Responsibilities:

1. License issuance and revocation
2. Compliance monitoring and enforcement
3. Incident response and investigation
4. Standard development and updating
5. Public transparency reporting

Decision Protocols:

· Routine decisions: Simple majority
· ME-Class licenses: 5-of-7 regional approval
· Emergency actions: 4-of-7 with expedited process
· Standard changes: 2/3 majority with public comment

7.2 The Public Transparency Mandate

Published Quarterly:

1. All issued licenses (anonymized for commercial sensitivity)
2. All revocations (with reasons)
3. All violation incidents (detailed analysis)
4. All orbital queries and responses (full spectrum)
5. Financial statements and funding sources

Real-Time Public Dashboards:

· Constellation health status
· License compliance statistics
· Energy consumption metrics
· Query volume and response times

Open Source Components:

· All reference implementations
· All testing tools
· All documentation
· All standards specifications

7.3 The Enforcement Hierarchy

First Layer: Automated Hardware Control

· IAGH TEE 3.2 enforcement
· Real-time monitoring and response
· No human intervention required for violations

Second Layer: NASAg Oversight

· Periodic audits and inspections
· License compliance verification
· Incident investigation and response

Third Layer: International Treaty

· ZENITH Accord (signatory nations)
· Mutual enforcement agreements
· Sanctions for non-compliance

Fourth Layer: Civil Society Monitoring

· Independent watchdog organizations
· Academic research and verification
· Public pressure and accountability

